    <title></title>
    <content type='html'>Thank you! To answer your question about this line:

&amp;quot;With only a couple of slips, which the casual listener never notices anyway, Odessa finished the song with a delighted [should that be &amp;quot;delightful&amp;quot;] trill?&amp;quot;

What I wanted to convey is that Odessa took delight in finishing the song with a trill, i.e. &amp;quot;delighted&amp;quot;.  Odessa is not an accomplished pianist, so her judgement as to the use of the trill might not be perfect, but she really likes adding it when she can.  I suppose it&amp;#39;s like a guitarist who likes to slide or hammer, even if the music doesn&amp;#39;t always call for those techniques...

By contrast, a trill is either *delightful* if it is played at the right time and executed properly, or it is *not delightful* if it&amp;#39;s poorly timed or executed.

So I think &amp;quot;delighted&amp;quot; conveys the meaning, but it&amp;#39;s a great question nevertheless.</content>
